The paper deals with automated classification of glioma nuclear shapes and visual attributes using Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) on pathology images. This involves computer vision (CV) techniques such as image segmentation, feature extraction, and classification. Therefore, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes methods to improve the performance of the CNN, which involves machine learning (ML) techniques such as semi-supervised learning, multi-task learning, and loss function design. Therefore, cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.LG (Machine Learning), and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) are also likely sub-categories. Finally, the paper deals with medical image analysis, which involves information retrieval (IR) techniques such as content-based image retrieval and medical image retrieval. Therefore, cs.IR (Information Retrieval) is also a likely sub-category.
